{"id":"astro-ph/0112223","submitter":"Anthony Minter","authors":"Anthony Minter and Felix J. Lockman","title":"G28.17+0.05, A Giant Atomic/Molecular Cloud","comments":"To appear in \"Proceedings of Seeing Through the Dust, The Detection\n  of HI and the Exploration of the ISM in Galaxies\", published by the\n  Astronomical Society of the Pacific, editors Russ Taylor, Tom Landecker, and\n  Tony Willis","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  HI 21 cm observations with the NRAO 140 Foot telescope have revealed a giant\nHI cloud (G28.17+0.05) in the Galactic plane that has unusual properties. The\ncloud is 150 pc in diameter, is at a distance of 5 kpc, and contains as much as\n100,000 Solar Masses of atomic hydrogen. The cloud consists of a cold core,\nT~10 K, and a hotter outer envelope, T < 200 K. There is no observable\ndifference in the HI line widths, ~7 km/s, between the core and the envelope.\nAnomalously-excited 1720 MHz OH emission, with a similar line width, is\nassociated with the core of the cloud. The cloud core also exhibits 12CO and\n13CO self-absorption which indicates that most of the cloud mass is in\nmolecules. The total mass of the cloud is greater than 200,000 Solar Masses.\nThe cloud has only a few sites of current star formation. If similar clouds are\nassociated with other observed sites of anomalously-excited 1720 MHz OH\nemission, there may be as many as 100 more of these objects in the inner\ngalaxy.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 10 Dec 2001 19:56:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
